00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:25.790
I'll begin my comments with
an excerpt from an interview

00:06:25.790 --> 00:06:28.500
by the founder of the World
Stage, the cofounder Kamau Daaood

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:33.500
who was speaking about his
understanding of the role of poets

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:36.910
and poetry inside of communities.

00:06:36.910 --> 00:06:40.840
Daaood is a veteran of
the Watch Writers Workshop

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:46.680
that you may have heard of as a
part of the Black Arts Movement.

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:50.520
He was also a part of the
Pan-Afrikan Peoples Arkestra,

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:57.030
which was led by the great composer
and pianist Mr. Horace Tapscott.

00:06:57.030 --> 00:07:00.360
He was the lead poet in
that particular organization

00:07:00.360 --> 00:07:02.470
and this is the quote about
again the role of artists

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:05.580
and poets in communities.

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:08.520
Quote, I am a devout poet.

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:12.160
I believe that right words offered

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:16.140
in the right way can be
music holding us together

00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:22.770
when we can speak the language of
essence, we will be able to commune

00:07:22.770 --> 00:07:27.400
in the space miles above
dogma in the confines

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:28.960
of individual traditions.

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:33.950
And we can develop into
evolved human beings capable

00:07:33.950 --> 00:07:39.640
of radiating profound love,
light and service to others.

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:45.080
I believe wholeheartedly that
art in a community is noble work

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:49.250
that fosters beauty and
meaning into our lives,

00:07:49.250 --> 00:07:52.380
that art is vital and necessary.

00:07:52.380 --> 00:07:56.190
I believe in the sacredness
of breathing.

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:59.930
I'll now read a poem developed
in that writing workshop

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:01.820
which meets every Wednesday night.

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:05.270
This poem is one of my own,
it's called the execution

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:11.130
of Michael Brown and
dot dot dot one.

00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:17.870
Unarmed white men don't catch
gunfire from riffle armed cops,

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:22.010
instead their empty palms wave
and pick winning raffle tickets

00:08:22.010 --> 00:08:24.160
from the policeman's ball.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:30.550
But black hands are magic, wallets
transform to firearms in the blink

00:08:30.550 --> 00:08:32.440
of a whaling mother's eye,

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:37.830
in the enchanting flash
of a service revolver.

00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:44.720
Black fingertips spin two 45's like
an old-school ballistic DJ flight

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:49.340
of hand too exquisite
for the veiled eye,

00:08:49.340 --> 00:08:53.430 position:56%
only visible in the cold of silence.

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:59.650
But come Sunday pistols are
missing imaginary planks in the eye

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:01.850
of the beholder of the bash.

00:09:01.850 --> 00:09:08.100
If you a speck in a brother's eye
it must be a glint from a handgun,

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:13.790
pluck it out, ask questions
later at the inquest.

00:09:13.790 --> 00:09:18.890
Let his unborn son cross-examine
the city's executioner,

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:23.180
let the womb question the
state, the Constitution.

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:31.960
Let his unborn son ask will black
magic make me disappear too.

00:09:31.960 --> 00:09:35.820
Ferguson is [inaudible],
a slave schooner

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:38.320
in a recycled Hennessey bottle.

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:45.410 position:56%
Sails are raised hands of surrender,
a loaded badge finds him guilty

00:09:45.410 --> 00:09:48.830
of harboring illegal dreams.

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:54.430
The bottle's waste constricts into
an hourglass meat grinder flips,

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:59.900
Michael Brown slides and tumbles
down a tunnel of no return.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:05.010
Time only moves backwards
when historians connect dots

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:12.970
like drunk demonologists or when
a sunken face mother whispers,

00:10:12.970 --> 00:10:17.340
I wish the magic bullet
would've hit me too.

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:19.150
Thank you.

00:10:19.150 --> 00:10:24.230
At the World Stage we try to
follow the spirit and dictates

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:27.210
of Mr. Kamau Daaood
who is our founder

00:10:27.210 --> 00:10:29.380
and also his cofounder
Billy Higgins.

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:31.540
If you are jazz fan
you may know the name.

00:10:31.540 --> 00:10:35.660
Billy Higgins was the house
drummer in many ways for Blue Note,

00:10:35.660 --> 00:10:40.350
the great jazz label here in New
York or Manhattan [inaudible],

00:10:40.350 --> 00:10:45.240
around the way in New York
[inaudible] oftentimes.

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:49.030
And so in many ways
we really are trying

00:10:49.030 --> 00:10:51.640
to address the present
historical moment

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:54.740
and this also links us back
to the 1960's movement.

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:56.160
As we know that in this time

00:10:56.160 --> 00:11:00.590
of really virulent
anti-blackness we can imagine,

00:11:00.590 --> 00:11:04.900
if you can imagine animus scale as
Mel White does where there's kind

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:07.320
of a hierarchy of aliveness
or animus.

00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:10.970
At the very bottom there may
be a rock and then some algae

00:11:10.970 --> 00:11:14.710
and the maybe a cat or a dog or
reverse if you're a dog person

00:11:14.710 --> 00:11:16.730
on up, you know, to people.

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:20.840
And the lower part of the human
animus scale are probably black men

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:22.140
and black women.

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:27.040
We have the least power to create
and produce change to alter this.

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:30.750
And at the very top we
probably find white men.

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:32.730
And at the surface --
at the current level

00:11:32.730 --> 00:11:36.060
of animus black folk
can be killed by someone

00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:38.940
and the killer can
suffer no consequence

00:11:38.940 --> 00:11:41.820
because our lives are devalued,
we have so little animus,

00:11:41.820 --> 00:11:43.950
a little aliveness and respect

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:45.830
in this modern present
historical moment

00:11:45.830 --> 00:11:49.500
that our lives are embodied
subjects don't matter enough

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:54.350
to even require the shooter,
the violator to go to prison

00:11:54.350 --> 00:11:56.910
or to even have a trial oftentimes,

00:11:56.910 --> 00:12:00.070
which is really very
frustrating and ridiculous.

00:12:00.070 --> 00:12:03.750
And so we believe that art can
make a change, art can change that.

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:07.190
Through art and through literature
in particular that we can use art

00:12:07.190 --> 00:12:09.920
to elevate the animus of people.

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:12.490
When you begin to tell your
own stories about your family,

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:14.260
about your mother,
about your mentors,

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:18.820
about your children you write
yourself into existence.

00:12:18.820 --> 00:12:22.150
And the power of writing own
narrative imagine any bookstore,

00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:26.110
a Barnes &amp; Noble or Borders or
Library of Congress when you

00:12:26.110 --> 00:12:28.100
and you pour that book from a shelf

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:29.960
or all those books
are someone's stories.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:32.740
It could be a nonfiction narrative,
it could be a book of poetry,

00:12:32.740 --> 00:12:34.580
it could be an imagine narrative.

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:37.380
What if you could tell
your own story?

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.550
What's implied about having so many
books in a library for example,

00:12:40.550 --> 00:12:42.090
like ours here at the
Library of Congress is

00:12:42.090 --> 00:12:45.360
that those lives were
worthy of documentation,

00:12:45.360 --> 00:12:49.130
worthy of a of a memoir,
worthy of a book of poems.

00:12:49.130 --> 00:12:51.740
What if black folks who
have a lower animus begin

00:12:51.740 --> 00:12:54.630
to tell their own stories
and that's the power

00:12:54.630 --> 00:12:56.780
of art we find in Los Angeles.

00:12:56.780 --> 00:13:00.670
When I got involved in 93 we began
to find creative ways to use art

00:13:00.670 --> 00:13:02.820
to reach people in our
neighborhood, in our community.

00:13:02.820 --> 00:13:06.120
So we would -- I live in
LA and we live right off

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:08.460
of Crenshaw Boulevard, there's a
neighborhood called Leimert Park,

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:12.270 position:56%
it's the center of black art and
political organizing in Los Angeles.

00:13:12.270 --> 00:13:14.740
It's also, you know, it's a
black working poor neighborhood

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:17.710
so we have gangsters, many of
them, we have drug dealers,

00:13:17.710 --> 00:13:20.720
many of them, we have black drama.

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:24.140
So we would go every Friday night
in the beginning especially in 93,

00:13:24.140 --> 00:13:29.740 position:56%
we'd go to a corner on 43rd off
Crenshaw with a few poets, a drummer

00:13:29.740 --> 00:13:32.820
and a milk crate and we would
get up and we would do poetry,

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:35.750 position:56%
we called it guerilla as in G-U-E-R.

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:38.710
Guerilla poetry live, we
start playing our drums

00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:41.460
and kicking our poetry on the
street of Crenshaw Boulevard.

00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:44.350
And of course invariably we
would have a drug dealer come by,

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:47.720
this is in 93 when
crack was ramped in LA.

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:50.760
Who are you people they
would kind of sweat us,

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:52.570
but we would say we're poets,

00:13:52.570 --> 00:13:55.980
we're beginning a poetry
workshop, please come.

00:13:55.980 --> 00:13:59.580 position:56%
And over a course of months of doing
this they begin to actually come

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:02.220
to a writing workshop
featuring poets.

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:07.010
So try to imagine in LA gangsters
and folks who are engaging

00:14:07.010 --> 00:14:10.850
in underground illicit commerce
coming to your poetry workshop.

00:14:10.850 --> 00:14:17.290 position:56%
It was for us, it was a time to not
dehumanize and make enemies of those

00:14:17.290 --> 00:14:19.480
who look like us because
oftentimes in black neighborhoods

00:14:19.480 --> 00:14:23.660
who are drug dealers or the
gangers are the outsiders

00:14:23.660 --> 00:14:24.960
for everyone in that neighborhood.

00:14:24.960 --> 00:14:27.540
So we try to find a way to
bring them inside the community

00:14:27.540 --> 00:14:29.680
by using art and by using poetry.

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:35.200
So we know the power of art
and poetry to transform lives.

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:37.930
And my own personal narrative,
I went to undergrad at Berkeley

00:14:37.930 --> 00:14:41.570
and my mentors were June
Jordan and Barbara Christian,

00:14:41.570 --> 00:14:44.200
the great scholar and theorist.

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:47.970
And I was in a very corporate track
as an undergraduate because I came

00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:49.790
from a very, very poor family,
I wanted to go make money

00:14:49.790 --> 00:14:52.220
for my family and I took as a lark,

00:14:52.220 --> 00:14:54.720
as an elective I took
Jean Jordan's poetry

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:59.990
for the people course one semester
the same quarter I Dr. Christian's

00:14:59.990 --> 00:15:01.370
course on literature.

00:15:01.370 --> 00:15:05.120
And being in those courses
literally changed my entire view

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:07.580
of myself, but also life itself.

00:15:07.580 --> 00:15:09.170
One day Barbara turned to
me, I would go to her house

00:15:09.170 --> 00:15:10.470
and she would send me to go buy rum

00:15:10.470 --> 00:15:13.480
which is probably inappropriate,
but to go buy rum.

00:15:13.480 --> 00:15:16.600
And we would go to her house
and we'd talk politics late

00:15:16.600 --> 00:15:18.720
into night almost every
single weekend.

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:22.200
And she turned to me one day
and she said, she shook me

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:28.680 position:56%
and she says Michael, you are going
to be somebody with such conviction,

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:34.130
with such a force, I mean she shook
me you're going to be somebody.

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:36.590
But I actually believed it myself.

00:15:36.590 --> 00:15:40.340
I began to believe it
myself, so I know the power

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:41.690
of someone believing in you.

00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:45.090
And you can believe in folks who
may be doing in your neighborhoods

00:15:45.090 --> 00:15:47.840
that are not progressive
or productive,

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:50.130
but you can still find
a way to believe in them

00:15:50.130 --> 00:15:51.430
if there's an access route.

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:54.480
And our access route
was art, it was poetry.

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:56.360
At the World Stage we offer
a seven days of program.

00:15:56.360 --> 00:16:00.320
We have drumming, African drumming,
we have poetry, we have jazz,

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:03.770 position:56%
we have a jazz [inaudible] for kids,
we have -- it's a crazy program.

00:16:03.770 --> 00:16:06.360
Go to the worldstage.org
for more information.

00:16:06.360 --> 00:16:10.070
And use these really inexpensive
five bucks per workshop

00:16:10.070 --> 00:16:11.960
for like the top people
in the world.

00:16:11.960 --> 00:16:14.420
Marcellis comes through,
all those cats come through,

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:16.360
Pharoah Sanders is
always coming through.

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:18.750
The biggest names in jazz
because we have Billy Higgins

00:16:18.750 --> 00:16:22.040
as our founder come to the
World Stage and kick their work

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:24.270
and of course the poets as well.

00:16:24.270 --> 00:16:27.890
As my time probably is wrapping up
here where's my -- how am I doing?

00:16:27.890 --> 00:16:29.190
We're doing great.

00:16:29.190 --> 00:16:32.820
And so we believe in the
power and the efficacy of art

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:34.740
to actually impact neighborhoods.

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:37.380
Too often as we know when
there's a financial crisis,

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:41.680
when there's a budget constraint
what gets cut first, the arts?

00:16:41.680 --> 00:16:46.680
That is a horrible shortsighted way
to approach living in a society.

00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:48.490
Because when you begin to take art

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:51.690
from neighborhoods you take
imagination from kids' lives.

00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:53.670
Imagination from adults' lives.

00:16:53.670 --> 00:16:58.390
When you lack imagination you go
to the lowest common denominator

00:16:58.390 --> 00:17:02.320
which is violence, which is
misogyny, which is homophobia,

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:05.500
which is trying to
imagine being a man

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:08.590
and a definition that's
this narrow right.

00:17:08.590 --> 00:17:12.770
It's not an expansiveness when
there is a lack of imagination.

00:17:12.770 --> 00:17:16.610
So we believe that through art,
through jazz, through literature,

00:17:16.610 --> 00:17:18.770
through poetry, through
children being exposed

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:20.910
to poets in their everyday life.

00:17:20.910 --> 00:17:22.580
If you can make for
children in particular,

00:17:22.580 --> 00:17:25.700
if you can make art
attractive or in our vernacular

00:17:25.700 --> 00:17:27.760
if you can make art cool right.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:31.230
So we thought a lot about how do we
make art cool enough for a gangster

00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:36.360 position:56%
to come to our workshop, for the guy
selling literally our corner crack

00:17:36.360 --> 00:17:37.660
cocaine literally.

00:17:37.660 --> 00:17:39.890
How do we make it cool enough
so we can get together?

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:42.190
So we begin to all wear
black leather jackets.

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:45.850
It was a small thing, we're
searching for straws right,

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:48.590
we're just -- let's all get
leather jackets and we'll go

00:17:48.590 --> 00:17:50.350
out to the corner and
we'll kick our poetry.

00:17:50.350 --> 00:17:53.570
I know very simplistic,
very kind of yeah,

00:17:53.570 --> 00:17:56.640
not really sophisticated,
but it helped right.

00:17:56.640 --> 00:17:59.820
And so to be able to walk
and talk and be around folks

00:17:59.820 --> 00:18:02.870
in the neighborhood who are just
open to us as other members living

00:18:02.870 --> 00:18:06.410
