the implicit declaration

00:27:14.290 --> 00:27:19.460
of our viability found in the
slogan, we shall overcome.

00:27:19.460 --> 00:27:25.320
But it also worries that basic
presumption when the onus

00:27:25.320 --> 00:27:30.940
of legitimizing that viability is
thrust onto us Blacks circling back

00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:36.310
to the tropes of an earlier age
is chastened in our language even

00:27:36.310 --> 00:27:40.910 position:56%
as we grapple with the continuing
onslaught of white racist aggression

00:27:40.910 --> 00:27:44.550
as the boulder comes down
upon our heads once more

00:27:44.550 --> 00:27:48.250
and we push it up yet again.

00:27:48.250 --> 00:27:53.800
We've moved from the solidity
authority of black power which said

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:59.780 position:56%
to us Blacks, no matter who else was
listening here it is and it is ours

00:27:59.780 --> 00:28:05.470
and let us see what it has
wrought and might yet produce.

00:28:05.470 --> 00:28:09.310
Almost 30 years ago when a
small group of aspiring writers

00:28:09.310 --> 00:28:10.680
and artists came together

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:15.100
in a project called the Dark
Room Collective we were operating

00:28:15.100 --> 00:28:20.710
under the spell of a devotion to
black lives and voices and art cast

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:24.770
by those literary elders and
ancestors who had paved the way

00:28:24.770 --> 00:28:29.930
with not just their works, but the
consciousness to be boldly in love

00:28:29.930 --> 00:28:34.360
with blackness and cognizant of
the social and political demands

00:28:34.360 --> 00:28:40.010
of history and the contemporary
moment on black lives.

00:28:40.010 --> 00:28:43.760
We meant the Dark Room to be a
space that celebrated the ways

00:28:43.760 --> 00:28:48.830
in which we could be free of our
constrictions, meaning ourselves

00:28:48.830 --> 00:28:51.340
and our audiences alike
in such a way

00:28:51.340 --> 00:28:54.830
that at the very least we can begin
to see each other more clearly

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:57.330
and support the ground,

00:28:57.330 --> 00:29:01.700
a non-exploitative ground
upon which to relate.

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:07.460
A yearning toward total life, the
language we put to it borrowing

00:29:07.460 --> 00:29:10.850
that phrase from Clarence Major.

00:29:10.850 --> 00:29:14.730
We didn't profess so much of
politics of blackness so much

00:29:14.730 --> 00:29:18.240
as a politics of community
built on acknowledgment

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:21.440
of our literary forebears
and forging bonds

00:29:21.440 --> 00:29:23.750
of generational dialogue
and mentorship.

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:29.380
As the official Dark Room
history goes James Baldwin's death

00:29:29.380 --> 00:29:31.450 position:56%
or more specifically, our pilgrimage

00:29:31.450 --> 00:29:35.660
to his funeral was the
genesis of the Dark Room.

00:29:35.660 --> 00:29:39.990
But Amiri Baraka really was the
prompt as it was he who urged us

00:29:39.990 --> 00:29:42.450
to go to Baldwin's funeral.

00:29:42.450 --> 00:29:46.060
In an essay I wrote many years ago

00:29:46.060 --> 00:29:50.870
for Mosaic Literary Magazine I
said this about that experience

00:29:50.870 --> 00:29:53.290
of attending Baldwin's funeral.

00:29:53.290 --> 00:29:56.990
Our sorrow was suffused
with a kind of energy,

00:29:56.990 --> 00:30:02.000
a desire to make something positive
out of loss and so we resolved

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:06.080
that we wouldn't let another of our
literary elders get away from us.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:10.830
In traditional black culture elders
are always teachers, role models.

00:30:10.830 --> 00:30:13.250
Through his writings and
activism, his humanism

00:30:13.250 --> 00:30:15.740
and his vision Baldwin
had given us an example

00:30:15.740 --> 00:30:18.210
of passionate engagement with life.

00:30:18.210 --> 00:30:21.170
Like the reels of West
African culture he

00:30:21.170 --> 00:30:23.070 position:56%
and other black writers bear witness

00:30:23.070 --> 00:30:25.330
to our collective struggles
and survival.

00:30:25.330 --> 00:30:29.560
And like countless other writers
before them they have made vital

00:30:29.560 --> 00:30:31.720 position:56%
contributions to American literature

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:34.130
and the African-American
artistic tradition,

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:37.870
as well as the global
literary tradition.

00:30:37.870 --> 00:30:41.130
We wanted to affirm the
sustaining value of the commitment

00:30:41.130 --> 00:30:44.000
and acknowledge our debt to them.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:47.200
My housemate Thomas Sayers
Ellis and I began to make plans

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:51.380
to formally connect with and honor
other still living black writers

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:55.360
whom we dubbed our
living literary ancestors.

00:30:55.360 --> 00:30:57.310
We were already involved
in a project

00:30:57.310 --> 00:31:00.470
of building an extensive library
of writings by black authors

00:31:00.470 --> 00:31:03.300
of the diaspora, including
first editions

00:31:03.300 --> 00:31:05.300
and out-of-print publications.

00:31:05.300 --> 00:31:09.360
We had named it the Dark Room
a Collection of Black Writing

00:31:09.360 --> 00:31:12.200
because it was housed in a
former photographing darkroom

00:31:12.200 --> 00:31:15.660
on the third floor of the
old Victorian house we shared

00:31:15.660 --> 00:31:17.970
with other artists and students.

00:31:17.970 --> 00:31:20.440
The words were already
emblazoned on the door

00:31:20.440 --> 00:31:25.470
and we liked the pun it provided
on a room full of black books.

00:31:25.470 --> 00:31:29.930
The metaphor of a darkroom was also
apt a place where images develop,

00:31:29.930 --> 00:31:35.950
brought forth in darkness
into light, incubator womb.

00:31:35.950 --> 00:31:40.640
Only afterwards did we realize the
affinity with the dark tower named

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:43.220
after County Collins'
poem The Gathering

00:31:43.220 --> 00:31:47.480
of Harlem Renaissance Artists
in A'Lelia Walker's salon.

00:31:47.480 --> 00:31:51.530
So in truth and in many ways
unconsciously too we had tapped

00:31:51.530 --> 00:31:53.490
into a continuum of historical

00:31:53.490 --> 00:31:58.340
and contemporary experiential
energy rooted in a consciousness

00:31:58.340 --> 00:32:01.880
of the beauty of our existence
and the commitment to Harold

00:32:01.880 --> 00:32:04.840
