Here I think too of Baraka's
language in referring

00:32:25.210 --> 00:32:28.290
to the importance of the
image in black consciousness.

00:32:28.290 --> 00:32:33.160
He refers to having the integrity
of those captured Africans.

00:32:33.160 --> 00:32:36.620
And also I think of Sonia
Sanchez's discussion of the artist

00:32:36.620 --> 00:32:39.070
as a creator of social values.

00:32:39.070 --> 00:32:42.810
So with the Black Arts Movement
we get this will and this sense

00:32:42.810 --> 00:32:49.310
of responsibility to create and
to create within a space of home.

00:32:49.310 --> 00:32:52.100
So that became I think the
framework for how we thought

00:32:52.100 --> 00:32:55.590
about the black literary
tradition in the Dark Room.

00:32:55.590 --> 00:32:59.980
How the project became meaningful
to us in terms of placing ourselves

00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:03.520
in relationship to the writers
who had paved the way for us

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:08.600
or as my cofounder colleague
Thomas put it, who we owed

00:33:08.600 --> 00:33:11.830 position:56%
and how we could extend their reach.

00:33:11.830 --> 00:33:14.740
In our mission and methods
we were emulating their ethos

00:33:14.740 --> 00:33:16.770
of fostering community.

00:33:16.770 --> 00:33:19.850
So for us the Dark Room reading
series had to be homegrown

00:33:19.850 --> 00:33:23.080
and grassroots, so to speak,
independent of settings

00:33:23.080 --> 00:33:24.680
such as academic institutions

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:28.030
of bookstores even
and initially it was.

00:33:28.030 --> 00:33:33.370
We held a series in our living
room, we opened the doors

00:33:33.370 --> 00:33:37.250
and invited the community in and
it was publicized pretty much

00:33:37.250 --> 00:33:41.830
by word-of-mouth and small flyers
and later go-go style posters,

00:33:41.830 --> 00:33:46.350
which is an homage to
Thomas's DC background.

00:33:46.350 --> 00:33:49.880
But we put them up all
around town in barbershops,

00:33:49.880 --> 00:33:51.980
in libraries, in stores, etcetera.

00:33:51.980 --> 00:33:55.150
In other words, we wanted
to have it in our home

00:33:55.150 --> 00:33:57.030
so that people could
feel comfortable,

00:33:57.030 --> 00:34:00.840 position:56%
they could feel at home in our home.

00:34:00.840 --> 00:34:03.810
We acknowledged the
generational bonds of community

00:34:03.810 --> 00:34:07.770
by pairing elder establish
writers with emerging ones

00:34:07.770 --> 00:34:11.130
and through this we aim to
highlight the implicit dialogue

00:34:11.130 --> 00:34:14.230
between the two readers'
works as well.

00:34:14.230 --> 00:34:17.970
This was important too because the
pairings were meant to acknowledge

00:34:17.970 --> 00:34:22.860
and promote too we hoped the
inherent mentorship of the elders

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:26.210
that we have within
Afrocentric tradition.

00:34:26.210 --> 00:34:29.090
Often the direct influence
of the elder writer's work

00:34:29.090 --> 00:34:31.300 position:56%
on the emerging writer was the basis

00:34:31.300 --> 00:34:35.280
for pairing the two
in the reading series.

00:34:35.280 --> 00:34:39.090
Also significantly we
added elements as hallmarks

00:34:39.090 --> 00:34:43.150 position:56%
of a specific cultural understanding
of ourselves and our audience.

00:34:43.150 --> 00:34:47.740
As a matter of cultural
specificity we added a jazz band,

00:34:47.740 --> 00:34:49.920
the Roxbury Blues Aesthetic.

00:34:49.920 --> 00:34:52.820
Roxbury along with
parts of Dorchester

00:34:52.820 --> 00:34:56.510
and Mattapan being the heart
of Boston's black community.

00:34:56.510 --> 00:34:59.870
Along with incorporating music
into the series we displayed art

00:34:59.870 --> 00:35:04.850 position:56%
by local black artists, students,
as well as more established artists.

00:35:04.850 --> 00:35:07.800
Bringing us all together and
often sharing meals together

00:35:07.800 --> 00:35:11.050
